        <title><m>\S I.4</m>: Connections to (classical) Logic</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Logic </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Determining whether something is true or false (or telling a computer how to do so)
                            is fundamental in computing. This requires <term>logic</term>. We'll introduce some basic
                            concepts and notation, as well as connections to sets.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Propositions and Operations</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            In classical logic, we deal with statements called <term>propositions</term>: statements
                            that are unambiguously true or false.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            "My name is Jeff" is a proposition because it is unambiguously true. "It is too hot today" is not
                            proposition. "<m>6-4=0</m>" is a proposition because it is unambiguously false.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There are a few basic operations we can perform on the propositions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\neg p</m>: "not <m>p</m>", called the <term>negation</term> of <m>p</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \wedge q</m>: "<m>p</m> and <m>q</m>", called the <term>conjunction</term> of <m>p</m>
                                        and <m>q</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \vee q</m>: "<m>p</m> or <m>q</m>", called the <term>disjunction</term> of <m>p</m>
                                        and <m>q</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

