            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Logic and Sets</title>
                    <statement>
                        
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <p>
                            Propositions are connected to sets because given a predicate <m>p(x)</m> (a proposition with a variable), we 
                            can build a corresponding set <m>P</m> such that <m>p(x)</m> is true exactly when <m>x \in P</m>. Under this
                            correspondence, 
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\neg p</m> corresponds to <m>P^C</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \wedge q</m> corresponds to <m>P \cap Q</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \vee q</m> corresponds to <m>P \cup Q</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Another important consequence is that we inherit all of the properties of sets (like <url href=" 
https://jshriner6.github.io/math156-FA2025/notes/sec-I-2-3-6.html#sec-I-2-3-6-5-1">distributive
                            laws</url> and <url href="
https://jshriner6.github.io/math156-FA2025/notes/sec-I-2-3-6.html#sec-I-2-3-6-5-4">DeMorgan's Laws</url>).
                        </p>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Conditional Statements</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We can combine propositions in two more important ways:
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \to q</m>: "If <m>p</m> then <m>q</m>", called a <term>conditional statement</term>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>p \longleftrightarrow q</m>: "If <m>p</m> if and only if <m>q</m>", called a <term>biconditional statement</term>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Example: Determining truth values of complicated propositions</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Determine the truth table for the proposition 
                            <me>
                                p \to q \to \neg p \vee q
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    
                </exercise>
